LazyColumn {
    items(comments.map { it.text }, key = { it }) { text ->
        CommentCard(text)
    }
}

answerCode:
Solution,
 🔨

At first glance, it looks like we’re doing everything right: we’re using the key parameter in items(), and we’re rendering a stable list.

But here’s the gotcha: we’re keying the list by the comment text, not by the actual unique identity of each comment.

If two comments have the same text — which is common in real apps — the key is no longer unique. This leads to Compose treating different items as the same, resulting in a crash when when a duplicate key is found as the list is being scrolled.

Fix: Always use a true stable identifier, like a comment ID: LazyColumn {
    items(comments, key = { it.id }) { comment ->
        CommentCard(comment.text)
    }
}

